        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our correlator set-up is motivated by the goal to determine the structure in the CO(1-0) line profiles of GMCs, which have line widths ranging from a few km/s to ~20 km/s for smaller and larger clouds, respectively.  In order to do this, we want at least a few spectral resolution elements per line width -- so a spectral resolution of 1 - 2 km/s will be sufficient.  We anticipate having to bin spectral windows to 2 km/s to achieve our target RMS.  In the worst case scenario, if the S/N is much less than expected, we will average spectral bins to ~3 km/s.  In the worst case scenario, for the narrowest line widths, we expect to have 2 or 3 resolution elements per line width.

NOTE: There are no lines strong enough that we specifically wish to target in the other basebands, so we filled them with continuum spectral windows.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We had to carefully consider the trade-off between angular and spectral resolution, while still being able to accomplish our science goals.  Part of the reason we selected NGC 625 as our target are the observational advantages, including the following: at the distance to this source (d=3.9 Mpc), we will be able to resolve relatively small GMCs and completely map the galaxy in just two pointings, in a reasonable amount of time.  The C36-3 Configuration at 115 GHz would yield an angular resolution of 1'', which at the distance to NGC 625 would result in a 20 pc resolution map.  This is sufficient to resolve relatively small GMCs and to resolve substructure within larger GMCs.  

Largest angular structures: 
In the Milky Way and beyond, the very largest GMCs are no bigger than ~ 100 pc across; at the distance to NGC 625, this corresponds to  largest angular structures (LAS) of 5.3'', well below the maximum recoverable scale (22'') of the C36-3 Configuration.  Thus, although the molecular ISM of galaxies certainly has a diffuse component, for our project, we are not concerned with missing emission that belongs to the GMCs we want to detect.  And given the expectation that typical low-metallicity GMCs are smaller than typical Galactic GMCs, we don't expect LAS's much greater than 100 pc.

To further anticipate the largest spatial scales, we used the ALMA Observation Tool to model a GMC at the distance to NGC 625.  Our model source is CO(1-0) data from a real, low-luminosity Galactic GMC about 100 pc across.  The simulated cloud, for which ~90% of the flux can be recovered in 1.5 hours of integration time, is shown in Figure 3 of the Science Justification.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To estimate the necessary RMS for our proposal, we started with the previous single-dish observations of Cormier et al. (2014).  This group used the ATNF Mopra 22-m telescope to measure a total CO(1-0) flux of about Ico = 2 K km/s per Mopra beam over a line width of 20 km/s.  Using the appropriate conversion (with the beam efficiency already accounted for), this corresponds to a flux density of  Snu = 14.52 Jy km/s per Mopra beam.  The areal filling fraction of giant molecular clouds (GMCs) per beam is unknown; but we ultimately settled on about 20%.    (Given the angular size of the galaxy, NGC 625, it is extremely unlikely that the emission is spread evenly, i.e., 100%, over the 30'' Mopra beam; and it is also unlikely that all the emission comes from a single point source.)

Our target resolution is 1'' (C36-3 Configuration).  Thus, we estimate the emission is spread over (30''/1'')^2 x 0.2 = 180 ALMA beams; and the flux density per synthesized ALMA beam would be 14.52 /180 = 80.7 mJy over 20 km/s.

Since we expect the smallest GMCs we resolve to have line widths no more than ~10 km/s, we desire a spectral resolution of at least 2 km/s.  In this case, the flux density would be spread over 10 channels, with an average flux density of 8.1 mJy per beam per channel.  Finally, to get a 5-sigma detection, we need an RMS of ~1.6 mJy beam per 2 km/s channel.

Even in an extremely pessimistic scenario, where we assume a filling fraction of 50%, the peak signal would be about 32 mJy over 20 km/s.  In this case, we could bin our spectral channels to 3 km/s (instead of 2 km/s), and still achieve a  &gt; 3-sigma detection.

SUMMARY:
Given: Single-dish: Ico = 2 K km/s,  dV = 20 km/s, D = 22 m  --&gt; 30'' at 115 GHz

Find: 	S = Ico (3514/D2) [Jy/K]
	S = 2 K km/s x (3514/222) = 14.52 Jy km/s per Mopra beam
Goal: 1''/ 2km/s angular/spatial resolution.
RMS needed:  1.6 mJy beam per 2 km/s channel</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
